---
import BlogShell from "../../layouts/BlogShell.astro";

const toc = [
  { id: "the-look", text: "The look", depth: 2 },
  { id: "chamfer", text: "Chamfer geometry", depth: 3 },
  { id: "type", text: "Type & tracking", depth: 3 },
  { id: "reading", text: "Reading container", depth: 2 },
];
---

<BlogShell title="Designing a monochrome HUD — Talos UI" toc={toc} back={{ href: "/blog/", text: "Back to blog" }}>
  <div class="talos-post-header">
    <h1>Designing a monochrome HUD</h1>
    <p class="talos-post-meta">
      <span>2026-06-05</span><span class="sep">/</span><span>6 min read</span>
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="glass-panel glass-panel--reading">
    <article class="glass-panel-content talos-prose">
      <p>
        This is the long-form reading container — a wider chamfer (24px), a
        lighter fill, and generous padding so prose stays comfortable above the
        ambient void. The HUD voice is deliberately softened here: headings drop
        the uppercase and wide tracking the rest of the system uses.
      </p>

      <h2 id="the-look">The look</h2>
      <p>
        Emphasis comes from contrast and geometry, never color. The whole system
        is one chamfered hairline chrome; rhythm comes from the mosaic and the
        type scale.
      </p>

      <h3 id="chamfer">Chamfer geometry</h3>
      <p>
        Corners are cut, not rounded. A two-layer technique paints an even 1px
        hairline along every edge including the angled cuts:
      </p>
      <pre><code>{`.glass-panel {
  clip-path: polygon(0 0, calc(100% - 14px) 0, 100% 14px, …);
}`}</code></pre>
      <p>
        Use <code>--talos-chamfer</code> to widen or tighten the cut. The
        <code>--reading</code> variant bumps it to 24px.
      </p>

      <h3 id="type">Type & tracking</h3>
      <p>
        Oxanium at weight 300, uppercase, <code>0.18em</code> tracking is the
        unmistakable HUD voice. Inside prose, headings revert to sentence case
        for readability.
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        Geometry and contrast over color — every panel is the same chrome.
      </blockquote>

      <h2 id="reading">Reading container</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Wider 24px chamfer for the larger surface</li>
        <li>Lighter fill so text doesn't sit on pure black</li>
        <li>Prose width capped at ~68ch</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        That's the blog layer: <code>talos-blog.css</code> on top of
        <code>talos.css</code>, plus the navbar pill and footer.
      </p>
    </article>
  </div>

  <footer class="talos-footer">
    <div class="glass-panel talos-pad">
      <div class="glass-panel-content talos-footer-grid">
        <div class="row" style="flex-direction:column;align-items:flex-start;gap:.5rem">
          <a class="talos-nav-link" href="/blog/">Blog</a>
          <a class="talos-nav-link" href="/docs/getting-started/">Docs</a>
          <a class="talos-nav-link" href="/mosaic/">Mosaic</a>
        </div>
        <div style="font-size:1.25rem">◢</div>
        <div>
          <p class="talos-eyebrow" style="margin:0 0 .5rem">Get in touch</p>
          <a class="talos-nav-link" href="mailto:joris@shelfwood.co">joris@shelfwood.co</a>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="talos-footer-note">© 2026 Shelfwood<span class="sep">/</span>All systems nominal</p>
    </div>
  </footer>
</BlogShell>
